{"title_page": "Joyce Jameson", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2009}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Joyce Jameson\n| image         = Joyce Jameson.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1932|09|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1987|01|16|1932|09|26}}\n| death_place   = [[Burbank, California]], U.S.\n| death_cause   = Suicide\n| resting_place = [[Cremains]] scattered into the [[Pacific Ocean]]\n| occupation    = Actress\n| yearsactive   = 1951\u20131984 \n| spouse        = [[Billy Barnes (composer)|Billy Barnes]]<br>({{abbr|m.|married}} 195?; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 19??)\n| children      = 1\n}}\n[[File:Joyce Jameson in General Electric Theater (Blaze of Glory).jpg|thumb|<center>Joyce Jameson in an episode of ''[[G.E. Theater]]'', \"Blaze of Glory\" (1958)</center>]]\n'''Joyce Jameson''' (September 26, 1932 \u2013 January 16, 1987) was an American actress, known for many television roles, including recurring guest appearances as Skippy, one of the \"fun girls\" in the 1960s television series ''[[The Andy Griffith Show]]'' as well as \"the Blonde\" in the [[Academy Award]]-winning ''[[The Apartment]]'' (1960).\n\n==Early years==\nJameson was born in Chicago.<ref name=ccct>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Erskine|title=Hollywood Today|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/10279218/the_corpus_christi_callertimes/|work=The Corpus Christi Caller-Times|agency=Newspaper Enterprise Association|date=July 18, 1960|location=Texas, Corpus Christi|page=29|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 14, 2017}} {{Open access}}</ref> She graduated from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] with a Bachelor of Arts degree.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gaver|first1=Jack|title='Shadow' for Monroe? Joyce Just Fits|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/10279729/the_salt_lake_tribune/|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|agency=United Press International|date=March 25, 1962|location=Utah, Salt Lake City|page=69|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 14, 2017}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Stage===\nJameson's [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] credits include ''Venus at Large'' (1961), ''The Billy Barnes People'' (1961) and ''[[The Billy Barnes Revue]]'' (1959).<ref>{{cite web|title=(\"Joyce Jameson\" search results)|url=http://www.playbill.com/searchpage/search?shows=on&people=on&theatres=on&q=Joyce+Jameson&qasset=00000150-ac7f-d16d-a550-ec7f03bb0001|website=Playbill Vault|publisher=Playbill|accessdate=15 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Films===\nJameson began work in the early 1950s with numerous uncredited roles in films and television. She made her film debut in 1951 playing a chorus girl dancer in the motion picture ''[[Show Boat (1951 film)|Show Boat]]''. Other notable film credits of that early period included ''Problem Girls'' (1953), ''[[Tip on a Dead Jockey]]'' (1957) and ''[[The Apartment]]''  (1960).\n\nIn 1962, she starred with [[Vincent Price]] and [[Peter Lorre]] in the [[Roger Corman]] horror film ''[[Tales of Terror]]'' as Annabel Herringbone. She played Lorre's vulgar, unfaithful wife, and during the course of the film, she and her paramour (Price) were locked up in Lorre's wine cellar. One year later, she again starred with Lorre and Price in the raucous comedy ''[[The Comedy of Terrors]]'' (released in 1964). In 1964, she appeared as a hotel hooker in the comedy ''[[Good Neighbor Sam]]'', starring [[Jack Lemmon]] and [[Romy Schneider]].\n\nIn 1966, she starred as Abigail in the [[Elvis Presley]] film ''[[Frankie and Johnny (1966 film)|Frankie and Johnny]]'' and in ''[[Boy, Did I Get a Wrong Number!]]'' with [[Bob Hope]] and [[Elke Sommer]]. She also appeared in 1968's ''[[The Split (film)|The Split]]'', a crime film with [[Jim Brown]] and [[Warren Oates]], and in an unsold comedy [[Television pilot|pilot]] for CBS titled ''[[The Mouse That Roared (film)#Television pilot|The Mouse That Roared]]''.\n\nJameson had roles in ''[[Death Race 2000]]'' (1975) playing Grace Pander, ''[[The Outlaw Josey Wales]]'' (1976) as Rose, ''[[Every Which Way but Loose (film)|Every Which Way but Loose]]'' (1978), and ''[[Hardbodies]]'' (1984).\n\n===Television===\nJameson was also a television actress. She was a regular member of the cast on ''Club Oasis''.{{r|etvs|page1=195}} She made two appearances on ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'': first as Lorraine Iverson who killed her husband in the 1963 episode \"The Case of the Floating Stones\", then as Dolly Jameson in the 1965 episode, \"The Case of the Feather Cloak\". She also had roles on ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]'' (in the episode \"A Day in the Life of Alan Brady\"), ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', ''[[Stagecoach West (TV series)|Stagecoach West]]'', ''[[The Twilight Zone]]'', ''[[McHale's Navy]]'', ''[[My Favorite Martian]]'', ''[[The Munsters]]'', ''[[F-Troop]]'', ''[[Hogan's Heroes]]'' (in the 1967 episode \"The Great Brinksmeyer Robbery\" as Mady Pleiffer),  ''[[Alias Smith and Jones]]'', ''[[Emergency!]]'' and ''[[Barney Miller]]''.  She appeared in ''[[The Rockford Files]]'' (in the 1974 episode \"The Dexter Crisis\" as Marge White). Later she appeared in ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'', ''[[The Feather and Father Gang]]'', and ''[[The Love Boat]]''.\n\nHer ongoing role as Skippy<ref name=\"etvs\">{{cite book|last1=Terrace|first1=Vincent|title=Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010|date=2011|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers|location=Jefferson, N.C.|isbn=978-0-7864-6477-7|page=43|edition=2nd}}</ref> paired with Daphne (played by [[Jean Carson]]) in ''[[The Andy Griffith Show]]'' established [[The Fun Girls]].\n\nJameson provided one of the voices for the cartoon series ''[[Jokebook]]''.{{r|etvs|page1=543}}\n\nJameson also was co-host of ''Tempo III'', a program on [[KCAL-TV|KHJ-TV]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vernon|first1=Terry|title=Progress Report on Ch. 9 Format|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/10279930/independent/|work=Independent|date=November 30, 1967|location=California, Long Beach|page=48|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 14, 2017}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe married to actor/songwriter [[Billy Barnes (composer)|Billy Barnes]] in the 1950s, and they had one child together, son Tyler, before their divorce.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-billy-barnes-20120926,0,7330940.story |title=Billy Barnes dies at 85; satirical songwriter for Hollywood revues |first=Dennis |last=McLellan |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2012-09-25 |access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Subsequently, Jameson was a longtime girlfriend of ''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'' star [[Robert Vaughn]]. She acted opposite Vaughn as the guest star on a 1966 ''U.N.C.L.E''. episode \"The Dippy Blond Affair\".\n\nAccording to Vaughn's autobiography, ''A Fortunate Life'', Jameson suffered from [[Clinical depression|depression]]. She was also an insomniac and regularly took [[Meprobamate|Miltown]] to help her sleep.<ref>{{cite book|last=Vaughn|first=Robert|title=A Fortunate Life|publisher=Macmillan|year=2008|pages=[https://archive.org/details/fortunatelife00vaug_0/page/88 88]|isbn=0-312-37112-8|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/fortunatelife00vaug_0/page/88}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn January 16, 1987, Jameson committed suicide by overdosing on pills at the age of 54.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsinreview.com/2007/01/01/camp-david-january-2007/4/|title=CAMP DAVID JANUARY 2007|last=Del Valle|first=David|date=2001-01-01|publisher=filmsinreview.com|page=4|accessdate=2009-05-13}}</ref> Her body was cremated and her ashes scattered at sea.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\" \n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | Film\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1951\n| ''[[Show Boat (1951 film)|Show Boat]]''\n| Chorus Girl\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1951\n| ''[[The Strip (1951 film)|The Strip]]''\n| Show Girl\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1951\n| ''[[The Son of Dr. Jekyll]]''\n| Barmaid \n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1953\n| ''[[Problem Girls]]''\n| Peggy Carstairs\n|\n|-\n| 1954\n| ''[[Phffft!]]''\n| Secretary \n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1956\n| ''[[Crime Against Joe]]''\n| Gloria Wayne\n|\n|-\n| 1956\n| ''[[Tension at Table Rock]]''\n| Singer\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1957\n| ''[[Tip on a Dead Jockey]]''\n| Sue Fan Finley\n| \n|-\n| 1960\n| ''[[The Apartment]]''\n| The Blonde\n|\n|-\n| 1962\n| ''[[Tales of Terror]]''\n| Annabel Herringbone\n| (segment \"The Black Cat\")\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[The Balcony (film)|The Balcony]]''\n| Penitent\n|\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[The Comedy of Terrors]]''\n| Amaryllis Trumbull\n|\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[Good Neighbor Sam]]''\n| Elsie Hooker\n|\n|-\n| 1966\n| ''[[Frankie and Johnny (1966 film)|Frankie and Johnny]]''\n| Abigail\n|\n|-\n| 1966\n| ''[[Boy, Did I Get a Wrong Number!]]''\n| Telephone operator\n|\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[The Split (film)|The Split]]''\n| Jennifer\n|\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[Death Race 2000]]''\n| Grace Pander\n|\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[The Outlaw Josey Wales]]''\n| Rose\n|\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[Scorchy]]''\n| Mary Davis \n| Alternative title: ''Race with Death'' \n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Every Which Way but Loose (film)|Every Which Way but Loose]]''\n| Sybil\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Pray TV (1980 film)|Pray TV]]''\n| Millie Peebles \n| Alternative title: ''K-GOD''\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''Ladies Night''\n| Emcee\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[The Man Who Loved Women (1983 film)|The Man Who Loved Women]]''\n|\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Hardbodies]]''\n| Rounder's Mom\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Lovelines (film)|Lovelines]]''\n| Mary Assquith \n| (final film role)\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | Television\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1956\n| ''[[Science Fiction Theatre]]''\n| Nina Lasalle\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1958\n| ''[[Playhouse 90]]''\n| Miss Cooper\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1959\n| ''[[Yancy Derringer]]''\n| Bonnie Mason \n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1960\n| ''[[The Betty Hutton Show]]''\n| Beverly Bell\n|\n|-\n| 1961\n| ''[[Lock-Up (TV series)|Lock-Up]]''\n| Coralee\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1961\u20131963\n| ''[[The Many Loves of Dobie Gillis]]''\n| Lola LaVerne \n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 1962\n| ''Outlaws''\n| Lotus\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1962\u20131965\n| ''[[Andy Griffith Show]]''\n| Skippy\n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[The Danny Thomas Show]]''\n| Nikki Stewart\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]''\n| Rosie Feather\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[McHale's Navy]]''\n| Kate O'Hara\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[The Twilight Zone (1959 TV series)|The Twilight Zone]]''\n| Starlet\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[Grindl]]''\n| Laverne\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[My Favorite Martian]]'' \n| Flossie\n| 1 Episode\n|-\n| 1965\n| ''[[The Baileys of Balboa]]''\n| Mary Brown\n| 1 episode\n|-\n|1965 & 1966\n|''[[The Munsters]]''\n|Miss Valentine & Lou\n|Season 1 Episode 23 & Season 2 Episode 16\n|-\n| 1966\n|''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]''\n| Jojo Tyler\n| Season 2 Episode 16\n|-\n| 1966\n| ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]''\n| Blanche\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1966\n| ''[[Gomer Pyle U.S.M.C.]]''\n| Irene \n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1966 & 1967\n| ''[[Hogan's Heroes]]''\n| Mady Pfeiffer <br> Eva Mueller\n| 1 episode <br> 1 episode\n|-\n| 1967\n| ''[[The Big Valley]]''\n| The Blonde\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1967\n| ''[[The Girl from U.N.C.L.E.]]''\n| Shirley Fummer\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1969\n| ''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]''\n| Millie\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1970\n| ''Run, Simon, Run''\n| Esther\n| Television movie<br>Alternative titles: ''Savage Run''<br>''The Tradition of Simon Zuniga''\n|-\n| 1971\n| ''[[Ironside (TV series)|Ironside]]''\n| Mrs. Akerman\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1972\n| ''[[Women in Chains]]''\n| Simpson\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1973\n| ''[[Here's Lucy]]''\n| Prisoner\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1974\n| ''[[Movin' On (TV series)|Movin' On]]''\n| Angela Wentworth\n| 1 episode\n|-\n|1974\n| ''[[The Rockford Files]]''\n| Marge White\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''The First 36 Hours of Dr. Durant''\n| Mrs. Graham\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1975\n| '' [[Barney Miller]]''\n| Catherine Lindsay\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[Baretta]]''\n| Lucille\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1977\n| ''The Feather and Father Gang''\n| Norma\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1978\n| ''[[Crash (1978 film)|Crash]]''\n| Sophie Cross \n| Television movie<br>Alternative title: ''Crash of Flight 401''\n|-\n| 1979\n| ''The Wild Wild West Revisited''\n| Lola (Showgirl)\n| Television movie\n|-\n| 1982\n| ''[[The Fall Guy]]''\n| Lucille\n| 1 episode\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|Film|Television|Theater}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0417055}}\n*{{IBDB name}}\n* {{Find a Grave|6486083}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jameson, Joyce}}\n[[Category:1932 births]]\n[[Category:1987 deaths]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Chicago]]\n[[Category:American actresses who committed suicide]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Drug-related suicides in California]]\n[[Category:20th-century American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{more citations needed|date=May 2009}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Joyce Jameson\n| image         = Joyce Jameson.jpg\n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1932|09|26}}\n| birth_place   = [[Chicago, Illinois]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1987|01|16|1932|09|26}}\n| death_place   = [[Burbank, California]], U.S.\n| death_cause   = Suicide\n| resting_place = [[Cremains]] scattered into the [[Pacific Ocean]]\n| occupation    = Actress\n| yearsactive   = 1951\u20131984 \n| spouse        = [[Billy Barnes (composer)|Billy Barnes]]<br>({{abbr|m.|married}} 195?; {{abbr|div.|divorced}} 19??)\n| children      = 1\n}}\n[[File:Joyce Jameson in General Electric Theater (Blaze of Glory).jpg|thumb|<center>Joyce Jameson in an episode of ''[[G.E. Theater]]'', \"Blaze of Glory\" (1958)</center>]]\n'''Joyce Jameson''' (September 26, 1932 \u2013 January 16, 1987) was an American actress, known for many television roles, including recurring guest appearances as Skippy, one of the \"fun girls\" in the 1960s television series ''[[The Andy Griffith Show]]'' as well as \"the Blonde\" in the [[Academy Award]]-winning ''[[The Apartment]]'' (1960).\n\n==Early years==\nJameson was born in Chicago.<ref name=ccct>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Erskine|title=Hollywood Today|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/10279218/the_corpus_christi_callertimes/|work=The Corpus Christi Caller-Times|agency=Newspaper Enterprise Association|date=July 18, 1960|location=Texas, Corpus Christi|page=29|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 14, 2017}} {{Open access}}</ref> She graduated from [[University of California, Los Angeles|UCLA]] with a Bachelor of Arts degree.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gaver|first1=Jack|title='Shadow' for Monroe? Joyce Just Fits|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/10279729/the_salt_lake_tribune/|work=The Salt Lake Tribune|agency=United Press International|date=March 25, 1962|location=Utah, Salt Lake City|page=69|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 14, 2017}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\n===Stage===\nJameson's [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] credits include ''Venus at Large'' (1961), ''The Billy Barnes People'' (1961) and ''[[The Billy Barnes Revue]]'' (1959).<ref>{{cite web|title=(\"Joyce Jameson\" search results)|url=http://www.playbill.com/searchpage/search?shows=on&people=on&theatres=on&q=Joyce+Jameson&qasset=00000150-ac7f-d16d-a550-ec7f03bb0001|website=Playbill Vault|publisher=Playbill|accessdate=15 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Films===\nJameson began work in the early 1950s with numerous uncredited roles in films and television. She made her film debut in 1951 playing a chorus girl dancer in the motion picture ''[[Show Boat (1951 film)|Show Boat]]''. Other notable film credits of that early period included ''Problem Girls'' (1953), ''[[Tip on a Dead Jockey]]'' (1957) and ''[[The Apartment]]''  (1960).\n\nIn 1962, she starred with [[Vincent Price]] and [[Peter Lorre]] in the [[Roger Corman]] horror film ''[[Tales of Terror]]'' as Annabel Herringbone. She played Lorre's vulgar, unfaithful wife, and during the course of the film, she and her paramour (Price) were locked up in Lorre's wine cellar. One year later, she again starred with Lorre and Price in the raucous comedy ''[[The Comedy of Terrors]]'' (released in 1964). In 1964, she appeared as a hotel hooker in the comedy ''[[Good Neighbor Sam]]'', starring [[Jack Lemmon]] and [[Romy Schneider]].\n\nIn 1966, she starred as Abigail in the [[Elvis Presley]] film ''[[Frankie and Johnny (1966 film)|Frankie and Johnny]]'' and in ''[[Boy, Did I Get a Wrong Number!]]'' with [[Bob Hope]] and [[Elke Sommer]]. She also appeared in 1968's ''[[The Split (film)|The Split]]'', a crime film with [[Jim Brown]] and [[Warren Oates]], and in an unsold comedy [[Television pilot|pilot]] for CBS titled ''[[The Mouse That Roared (film)#Television pilot|The Mouse That Roared]]''.\n\nJameson had roles in ''[[Death Race 2000]]'' (1975) playing Grace Pander, ''[[The Outlaw Josey Wales]]'' (1976) as Rose, ''[[Every Which Way but Loose (film)|Every Which Way but Loose]]'' (1978), and ''[[Hardbodies]]'' (1984).\n\n===Television===\nJameson was also a television actress. She was a regular member of the cast on ''[[Club Oasis]]''.{{r|etvs|page1=195}} She made two appearances on ''[[Perry Mason (TV series)|Perry Mason]]'': first as Lorraine Iverson who killed her husband in the 1963 episode \"The Case of the Floating Stones\", then as Dolly Jameson in the 1965 episode, \"The Case of the Feather Cloak\". She also had roles on ''[[The Dick Van Dyke Show]]'' (in the episode \"A Day in the Life of Alan Brady\"), ''[[Gunsmoke]]'', ''[[Stagecoach West (TV series)|Stagecoach West]]'', ''[[The Twilight Zone]]'', ''[[McHale's Navy]]'', ''[[My Favorite Martian]]'', ''[[The Munsters]]'', ''[[F-Troop]]'', ''[[Hogan's Heroes]]'' (in the 1967 episode \"The Great Brinksmeyer Robbery\" as Mady Pleiffer),  ''[[Alias Smith and Jones]]'', ''[[Emergency!]]'' and ''[[Barney Miller]]''.  She appeared in ''[[The Rockford Files]]'' (in the 1974 episode \"The Dexter Crisis\" as Marge White). Later she appeared in ''[[Charlie's Angels]]'', ''[[The Feather and Father Gang]]'', and ''[[The Love Boat]]''.\n\nHer ongoing role as Skippy<ref name=\"etvs\">{{cite book|last1=Terrace|first1=Vincent|title=Encyclopedia of Television Shows, 1925 through 2010|date=2011|publisher=McFarland & Company, Inc., Publishers|location=Jefferson, N.C.|isbn=978-0-7864-6477-7|page=43|edition=2nd}}</ref> paired with Daphne (played by [[Jean Carson]]) in ''[[The Andy Griffith Show]]'' established [[The Fun Girls]].\n\nJameson provided one of the voices for the cartoon series ''[[Jokebook]]''.{{r|etvs|page1=543}}\n\nJameson also was co-host of ''Tempo III'', a program on [[KCAL-TV|KHJ-TV]] in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vernon|first1=Terry|title=Progress Report on Ch. 9 Format|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/10279930/independent/|work=Independent|date=November 30, 1967|location=California, Long Beach|page=48|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 14, 2017}} {{Open access}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nShe married to actor/songwriter [[Billy Barnes (composer)|Billy Barnes]] in the 1950s, and they had one child together, son Tyler, before their divorce.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-billy-barnes-20120926,0,7330940.story |title=Billy Barnes dies at 85; satirical songwriter for Hollywood revues |first=Dennis |last=McLellan |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=2012-09-25 |access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> Subsequently, Jameson was a longtime girlfriend of ''[[The Man from U.N.C.L.E.]]'' star [[Robert Vaughn]]. She acted opposite Vaughn as the guest star on a 1966 ''U.N.C.L.E''. episode \"The Dippy Blond Affair\".\n\nAccording to Vaughn's autobiography, ''A Fortunate Life'', Jameson suffered from [[Clinical depression|depression]]. She was also an insomniac and regularly took [[Meprobamate|Miltown]] to help her sleep.<ref>{{cite book|last=Vaughn|first=Robert|title=A Fortunate Life|publisher=Macmillan|year=2008|pages=[https://archive.org/details/fortunatelife00vaug_0/page/88 88]|isbn=0-312-37112-8|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/fortunatelife00vaug_0/page/88}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nOn January 16, 1987, Jameson committed suicide by overdosing on pills at the age of 54.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsinreview.com/2007/01/01/camp-david-january-2007/4/|title=CAMP DAVID JANUARY 2007|last=Del Valle|first=David|date=2001-01-01|publisher=filmsinreview.com|page=4|accessdate=2009-05-13}}</ref> Her body was cremated and her ashes scattered at sea.\n\n==Filmography==\n{| border=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 90%;\" \n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | Film\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1951\n| ''[[Show Boat (1951 film)|Show Boat]]''\n| Chorus Girl\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1951\n| ''[[The Strip (1951 film)|The Strip]]''\n| Show Girl\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1951\n| ''[[The Son of Dr. Jekyll]]''\n| Barmaid \n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1953\n| ''[[Problem Girls]]''\n| Peggy Carstairs\n|\n|-\n| 1954\n| ''[[Phffft!]]''\n| Secretary \n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1956\n| ''[[Crime Against Joe]]''\n| Gloria Wayne\n|\n|-\n| 1956\n| ''[[Tension at Table Rock]]''\n| Singer\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1957\n| ''[[Tip on a Dead Jockey]]''\n| Sue Fan Finley\n| \n|-\n| 1960\n| ''[[The Apartment]]''\n| The Blonde\n|\n|-\n| 1962\n| ''[[Tales of Terror]]''\n| Annabel Herringbone\n| (segment \"The Black Cat\")\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[The Balcony (film)|The Balcony]]''\n| Penitent\n|\n|-\n| 1963\n| ''[[The Comedy of Terrors]]''\n| Amaryllis Trumbull\n|\n|-\n| 1964\n| ''[[Good Neighbor Sam]]''\n| Elsie Hooker\n|\n|-\n| 1966\n| ''[[Frankie and Johnny (1966 film)|Frankie and Johnny]]''\n| Abigail\n|\n|-\n| 1966\n| ''[[Boy, Did I Get a Wrong Number!]]''\n| Telephone operator\n|\n|-\n| 1968\n| ''[[The Split (film)|The Split]]''\n| Jennifer\n|\n|-\n| 1975\n| ''[[Death Race 2000]]''\n| Grace Pander\n|\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[The Outlaw Josey Wales]]''\n| Rose\n|\n|-\n| 1976\n| ''[[Scorchy]]''\n| Mary Davis \n| Alternative title: ''Race with Death'' \n|-\n| 1979\n| ''[[Every Which Way but Loose (film)|Every Which Way but Loose]]''\n| Sybil\n|\n|-\n| 1980\n| ''[[Pray TV (1980 film)|Pray TV]]''\n| Millie Peebles \n| Alternative title: ''K-GOD''\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''Ladies Night''\n| Emcee\n|\n|-\n| 1983\n| ''[[The Man Who Loved Women (1983 film)|The Man Who Loved Women]]''\n|\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Hardbodies]]''\n| Rounder's Mom\n|\n|-\n| 1984\n| ''[[Lovelines (film)|Lovelines]]''\n| Mary Assquith \n| (final film role)\n|-\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! colspan=\"4\" style=\"background: LightSteelBlue;\" | Television\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\" align=\"center\"\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 1956\n| ''[[Science Fiction Theatre]]''\n| Nina Lasalle\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1958\n| ''[[Playhouse 90]]''\n| Miss Cooper\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1959\n| ''[[Yancy Derringer]]''\n| Bonnie Mason \n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1960\n| ''[[The Betty Hutton Show]]''\n| Beverly Bell\n|\n|-\n| 1961\n| ''[[Lock-Up (TV series)|Lock-Up]]''\n| Coralee\n| 1 episode\n|-\n| 1961\u20131963\n| ''[[The Many Loves of Dobie Gillis]]''\n| Lola LaVerne \n| 3 episodes\n|-\n| 1962\n| ''